  "title": "2023-01-03",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6cc772b41f300925",
      "text": "⇒ [[Addressability]] ⇒ Adressabilität als Grundbegriff der soziologischen Systemtheorie"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "58d89dcb8fded14c",
      "text": "FUCHS, Peter, 2006. Vom Zögling zum Formen-Topf. Das Adressenformular der Erziehung. Soziale Systeme. 2006. Vol. 12, no. 2, p. 383–402. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2749c7b898d7997f",
      "text": "[[Education]] may be a laborious and therefore sometimes pitiable business, but the figure that makes it possible seems simple, seems evident. To [[educate]] means: to [[change]] [[People]] in difference to a self-propelling socialization (and: in good intention). It is presupposed that one can actually bring about this change and that one can do it purposefully, further that the effects of education can be distinguished from socialization effects, then that the person to be educated is somehow in a state of incompleteness, the educator rather in a state of 'non-incompleteness', finally that there is someone in play who educates and someone who is educated: Educator and pupil, if one wants to put it in an antiquated way, a role-like complementarity that juxtaposes educational action and its counterpart, a kind of receptivity or receptaculum."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c5e7ae20eb26976a",
      "text": "One can assume that this idea is still convincing in the robust lack of concern of everyday education, but not that the reflective instance of the educational system, pedagogy, has not long since noticed that things are much more complicated, even more complex. Who is being educated is the question; who or what is that on which the 'wanted' or 'intended' change takes place? Is there something behind the cloak of flesh that covers the inside opaquely: a spirit, an identity, a subject even? Are we dealing with lining systems? How can one intervene, direct, control what is hidden inside if one does not and can never become aware of it? And why should this internal instance change in self-contact if it does not have to (on the basis of freedom, another myth typical of education)?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bae2bc231372e220",
      "text": "These are well-known 'brooding questions', to which the theory represented here does not give answers, because it does not ask them in this way. They are questions which - without doubt - keep communication about education in operation, but which could perhaps be avoided, even discarded, if one departs from that everyday plausible model and instead assumes that what is covered by those questions can be designated by the idea and theory of [[Addressability]]. From this piece of theory it can even be foreseen - so the thesis - with which special problem education has to struggle, if it is to take place under world-social conditions.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "048b57b6d6711463",
      "text": "What a theoretically minded observer can see (and: what he cannot see) depends on the design of the theory he takes as a basis and on the fact that he can observe from there how the world district he takes into view 'de-signs' itself and its basic assumptions. The self-design of education has its functioning ontology in the features sketched above and in any case in the fact that it cannot but assume that education educates someone. There are people who educate or on whom education is educated. The event space of education is punctuated with people who act, and what happens between them is somehow 'interpersonal', is 'intersubjective', is thematizable as a complex set of relations between people."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7956b2c6d633f9ef",
      "text": "The systems theory that is in play here (that of the so-called 'Bielefeld School'), on the other hand, abstracts so strongly that the 'complex visual images' of education are 'blown up'. The scandalizing effect of this theory can be found from the beginning in the fact that it does not start from a 'plug-in world' in which everything that occurs is in something that still has something in it, for example people in society and in people the psyche, but from the fact that the world of meaning can be ordered along the system/environment difference. To put it in a nutshell: System theory understands education as an operation of a closed functional system and the people who are relevant for this system (here: those to be educated) as the environment or co-environment of this very system."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "41871ee4d26b13d6",
      "text": "This leads to the question of how this co-world is represented in the social system of education. The answer is: in the form of the social address. It is the social structure which - 'moored' at the anchor point of the proper name - directs, as it were, in which way and to what extent 'people' can be communicatively addressed. Social addresses are classically 'bundles of behavioral expectations', in our context, however, they are combination scopes by means of which it is continuously decided whether the behavior of people fits socially or not, and even whether this behavior is taken up at all for the continuation of communication (of communication!)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "baf363fa4e4ce0e0",
      "text": "It is quite important that the social address is not confused with the psychosomatic complex usually called human being, person, individual, etc. This complex is, if you like, 'demonic', unpredictable, in its self-reference not accessible for social systems. It is not even communicable if and insofar as it is cogent that social systems process not consciousness but communications. What is at stake in the theory piece of social address is only whether and how the co-world (the relevant environment) gets involved in the game of sociality."
    },
