      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "2749c7b898d7997f",
        "text": "Education may be a laborious and therefore sometimes pitiable business, but the figure that makes it possible seems simple, seems evident. To educate means: to change people in difference to a self-propelling socialization (and: in good intention). It is presupposed that one can actually bring about this change and that one can do it purposefully, further that the effects of education can be distinguished from socialization effects, then that the person to be educated is somehow in a state of incompleteness1 , the educator rather in a state of 'non-incompleteness', finally that there is someone in play who educates and someone who is educated: Educator and pupil, if one wants to put it in an antiquated way, a role-like complementarity that juxtaposes educational action and its counterpart, a kind of receptivity or receptaculum."
